{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option B -- use our terms throughout, split only for 德",
    "content": "**Option B -- use our dictionary terms (humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct) in both the block quote and the analysis.**\n\nThe logic that justified the split for 德 does not apply to 仁/义/礼. Here is why:\n\nThe 德 split works because the author is making a *philosophical argument* that 德-as-traditionally-understood (virtue) is not what 德 actually is (character). The terminological shift enacts the conceptual shift. The reader needs to see \"virtue\" first to feel the reversal.\n\nFor 仁/义/礼, the author is NOT arguing that these terms mean something fundamentally different from their traditional senses. The author's 现象仁 is still recognizably humaneness -- the argument is about *where it comes from* (bottom-up from phenomena, not top-down from 道), not about *what it is*. Switching from \"benevolence\" to \"humaneness\" mid-passage would create a terminological disruption without a corresponding conceptual payoff. The reader would just be confused about whether these are the same terms.\n\nAdditionally, \"humaneness\" and \"rightness\" are themselves legitimate scholarly renderings of 仁 and 义 -- they are not idiosyncratic departures. The reader familiar with DDJ Ch. 38 will recognize the passage regardless of whether 仁 is rendered \"benevolence\" or \"humaneness.\" These are within the normal range of variation in Laozi translations. \"Virtue\" vs. \"character\" for 德 is a genuine departure; \"humaneness\" vs. \"benevolence\" for 仁 is not.\n\nKeep the split for 德 only. Use our terms for everything else throughout."
  }
}
